---
import BaseHead from '../components/BaseHead.astro';
import Header from '../components/Header.astro';
import Footer from '../components/Footer.astro';
import { SITE_TITLE } from '../consts';
---

<!doctype html>
<html lang="en">
  <head>
    <BaseHead title={`About — ${SITE_TITLE}`} description="Why the Armor Freight Journal exists, and who writes it." />
  </head>
  <body class="bg-white text-af-ink">
    <Header />
    <main class="mx-auto max-w-3xl px-6 py-16">
      <header class="mb-10">
        <p class="text-sm font-bold uppercase tracking-[0.3em] text-af-green-dark">About</p>
        <h1 class="mt-4 text-4xl font-extrabold tracking-tight leading-tight md:text-5xl">
          Freight, from the people who actually move it.
        </h1>
      </header>

      <div class="prose prose-lg prose-neutral max-w-none">
        <p>The Armor Freight Journal is a publication about how freight actually works — written by people who have spent their careers in it, not observing it.</p>

        <p>Most writing about logistics falls into one of two buckets: dry technical explainers, or marketing copy dressed up as insight. This is neither. The pieces here come out of real operational experience — the loads that went sideways, the models that quietly cost more than they saved, the difference between the cheapest quote and the cheapest outcome. The kind of thing you only learn by being responsible for the freight when something breaks.</p>

        <p>The perspective is grounded in more than a decade behind the wheel before any of it moved into an office. That matters, because freight looks different depending on where you're standing. The view from a dispatch desk isn't the view from the cab, and the view from a rate sheet isn't the view from a receiver's dock at 4:55 on a Friday. The writing here tries to hold all of those at once.</p>

        <p>The Journal is published by <a href="https://armorfreight.com">Armor Freight Services</a>, a freight, warehousing, and distribution operation serving the Northeast, Southeast, and Midwest — with hubs in the Lehigh Valley / Allentown, Pennsylvania, and Jacksonville, Florida. But this isn't a sales channel. The articles are written to be useful and true whether or not you ever ship a thing with us. If they happen to make the case for how we think about freight, that's because the way we write about it is the way we run it.</p>

        <h2>What you'll find here</h2>

        <p><strong>Essays</strong> — operational opinion. Why most freight companies fail during exceptions. Why the cheapest quote isn't the cheapest load. The arguments we'd make over coffee with someone who runs a shipping operation.</p>

        <p><strong>Case studies</strong> — how a particular approach worked, and why. Not testimonials, not brochures. Operational analysis of real problems and what actually solved them.</p>

        <p>The throughline is the same one Armor Freight runs the business on: earn the work one load and one lane at a time, then keep it over the long haul. That only happens if the freight shows up the way you said it would — which is what most of these pieces are really about.</p>

        <p>If any of it is useful to you, that's the point. And if you're ever moving freight where the way it's handled matters more than the rate, <a href="https://armorfreight.com">that's the conversation we're built for</a>.</p>
      </div>
    </main>
    <Footer />
  </body>
</html>